in the text, here seems to be used with a consciousness of its
etymology, as St. Paul plays on the word in <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.vii-p7.3"></span>οὐκ ἐδοκίμασαν</span>.

<span id="fn_1232"></span>[i:1233](1110068.htm#fr_1232.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p16.1"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p17"></span> The author seems here to overlook the
fact that Paul at the beginning of ch. ii. turns to the Jews. Chrys.
speaks as if he were now addressing specifically “rulers.” But as the
argument goes on, the language shows more and more clearly that he is
here thinking of the Jewish world (see [Rom.
2.12-17](../../../bib/kjv/rom002.htm#012.md)<span
id="vii.vii-p17.1"></span>). The “therefore” grounds the fact of
universal condemnation upon the description of sin as universal,
contained in [Rom. 1.18-32](../../../bib/kjv/rom001.htm#018.md)<span
id="vii.vii-p17.2"></span>. The only peculiarity is that the statement
that this picture of Gentile depravity is a picture of universal
application, is made afterwards, “For wherein,” etc. The argument
proceeds as if after [Rom. 1.32](../../../bib/kjv/rom001.htm#032.md)<span
id="vii.vii-p17.3"></span> the apostle had been interrupted with the
objection, “But your description does not apply to us.” The apostle
answers: “It does, for you do the same things.” The “therefore” is
proleptic so far as it assumes as shown what he now asserts: <span
class="Greek"><span id="vii.vii-p17.4"></span>τὰ γὰρ ἀυτὰ πράσσεις ὁ
κρίνων</span>. The conclusion is thus stated before the major
premiss.—G.B.S.

