id="vii.vii-p40.1"></span>ἐ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.vii-p40.2"></span>πετείχισεν</span>, strictly, attacked him by
planting in his heart the thought of that fearful day.

<span id="fn_1238"></span>[i:1239](1110068.htm#fr_1238.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p44.1"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p45"></span> [Rom.
2.12](../../../bib/kjv/rom002.htm#012.md)<span id="vii.vii-p45.1"></span>
assigns the ground of [Rom. 2.11](../../../bib/kjv/rom002.htm#011.md)<span
id="vii.vii-p45.2"></span>. “Sin brings penalty and death whether
committed under the Mosaic law or under the ethical law of conscience.”
The first member of the sentence ([Rom.
2.12](../../../bib/kjv/rom002.htm#012)<span id="vii.vii-p45.3"></span>.md)
applies to the Gentiles. They have sinned without the standard and
guidance of positive law; they are, therefore, not brought to the test
of that law’s demands, but to the tests of natural, moral law (which the
apostle will directly describe), and by that test their sins meet their
penalty. Death, as sin’s penalty, is coextensive with *sin,* not with
the Mosaic law. Sin existed before the Mosaic law and apart from it; it
is imputed to the Gentiles—not, indeed in the same way and degree ([Rom.
v. 13](../../../bib/kjv/rom005.htm#013.md)<span
id="vii.vii-p45.4"></span>)—because they have a law of conscience. Each
class is judged by the standard which has been given to them. All the
terms relating to *law* here signify the Mosaic law, which was to Paul
the specific statutory expression of the divine will and the embodiment
of moral principles and duties.—G.B.S.

<span id="fn_1239"></span>[i:1240](1110068.htm#fr_1239.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p47.1"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p48"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.vii-p48.1"></span>πρῶτος σοῦ</span> cf. St. [John i.
30](../../../bib/kjv/joh001.htm#030.md)<span id="vii.vii-p48.2"></span>.

<span id="fn_1240"></span>[i:1241](1110068.htm#fr_1240.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p53.1"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p54"></span> αὐτάρκης, writing before the Pelagian
controversy, he does not notice the distinction between a sufficiency of
knowledge, etc., and a supply of grace which must be presupposed. See
Aug. *ad Dardanum*, *Ep*. 188, al. 143, c. 11, 12. See also De C. D. x.
c. 29 and 32. Conc. Araus. <span class="c14"><span
id="vii.vii-p54.1"></span>a.d.</span> 529, cap. 19. Labbe IV. 1670, B.
declares grace needed even before the fall, much more after. See Bp.
Bull on the state of man before the fall, Works, II. also Vinc. Lir. c.
24. The question is here whether men had means to attain salvation. It
is taken for granted they had power given them to choose the right, but
whether in the way of nature or of grace it is not defined. The grace
given to Christians was always regarded as so distinct from and superior
to everything granted to Jews or Heathens, that it was difficult to
speak of the manner in which they received Divine assistance. But the
gift spoken of by Justin Martyr, [Ap. i.
13](../../../bib/kjv/rev001.htm#013.md)<span id="vii.vii-p54.2"></span>, is
clearly supernatural. See also, St. Basil, *Const. Mon*. 16, t. 2, p.
559, B. and Macarius, Hom. 56.

<span id="fn_1241"></span>[i:1242](1110068.htm#fr_1241.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p55.11"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p56"></span> Perhaps human “messengers,” inspired
teachers other than those strictly called Prophets.

<span id="fn_1242"></span>[i:1243](1110068.htm#fr_1242.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p56.9"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p57"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.vii-p57.1"></span>The <span class="c14"><span
id="vii.vii-p57.2"></span>ms</span>. reading means no more: but the Edd.
have</span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.vii-p57.3"></span>μυριομακαριότης</span> <span
class="Greek"><span id="vii.vii-p57.4"></span>“Countless blessedness,”
which is more like St. Chrysostom than a copyist.</span>

<span id="fn_1243"></span>[i:1244](1110068.htm#fr_1243.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p57.5"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p58"></span> Origen on [Matt. xxvi.
69](../../../bib/kjv/mat026.htm#069.md)<span id="vii.vii-p58.1"></span>,
notices the same. Ed. Ben. p. 913, D.

<span id="fn_1244"></span>[i:1245](1110068.htm#fr_1244.md) <span
id="vii.vii-p58.8"></span>

<span id="vii.vii-p59"></span> ἔρως…φιλία: the whole of this glorious
passage suffers grievously in translation, owing to the impossibility of
expressing the climax from ἀγαπᾶν, the common ecclesiastical word, to
φιλεῖν and even ἐρᾶν.

